<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sequenced specimens from the new Hesperiidae subfamilies. DNA sample numbers are given for each specimen, additional data are in the Suppl. material 1: Table S 1 a Ortholexis holocausta syntype, NVG- 18053 C 02 b Ortholexis hollandi, NVG- 18082 A 08 c Ortholexis melichroptera, holotype of Acallopistes dimidia Holland, 1896; NVG- 18053 C 05 d Ortholexis melichroptera, holotype, NVG- 18053 A 06 e Katreus johnstonii, NVG- 18053 B 05 f Chamunda chamunda, NVG- 18086 E 02 g Barca bicolor, NVG- 17069 C 10 h Apostictopterus fuliginosus, NVG- 17069 C 12." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.861.34686.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/315261" pageId="8" pageNumber="99">Fig. 1g</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apostictopterus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apostictopterus" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="99">Apostictopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Leech, [1893] with its subjective synonym 
<taxonomicName genus="Tecupa" lsidName="Tecupa" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="99">Tecupa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Swinhoe, 1917 (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sequenced specimens from the new Hesperiidae subfamilies. DNA sample numbers are given for each specimen, additional data are in the Suppl. material 1: Table S 1 a Ortholexis holocausta syntype, NVG- 18053 C 02 b Ortholexis hollandi, NVG- 18082 A 08 c Ortholexis melichroptera, holotype of Acallopistes dimidia Holland, 1896; NVG- 18053 C 05 d Ortholexis melichroptera, holotype, NVG- 18053 A 06 e Katreus johnstonii, NVG- 18053 B 05 f Chamunda chamunda, NVG- 18086 E 02 g Barca bicolor, NVG- 17069 C 10 h Apostictopterus fuliginosus, NVG- 17069 C 12." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.861.34686.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/315261" pageId="8" pageNumber="99">Fig. 1h</figureCitation>
). Both valid genera are monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="99" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="99">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="99">
These two genera from southwestern China were (with disclaimers) placed in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heteropterinae">Heteropterinae</taxonomicName>
by Evans (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.105941" author="Evans, WH" journalOrPublisher="British Museum (Natural History), London" pageId="11" pageNumber="102" refId="B9" refString="Evans, WH, 1949. A Catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia, and Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). . British Museum (Natural History), London" title="A Catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia, and Australia in the British Museum (Natural History)." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.105941" year="1949">Evans 1949</bibRefCitation>
) and transferred to 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hesperiinae">Hesperiinae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.2008.00463.x" author="Warren, AD" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="12" pageNumber="103" pagination="467 - 523" refId="B27" refString="Warren, AD, Ogawa, JR, Brower, AVZ, 2009. Revised classification of the family Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera: Hesperioidea) based on combined molecular and morphological data. . Systematic Entomology 34: 467 - 523" title="Revised classification of the family Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera: Hesperioidea) based on combined molecular and morphological data." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.2008.00463.x" volume="34" year="2009">Warren et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, owing to different from 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heteropterinae">Heteropterinae</taxonomicName>
genitalia. Mitochondrial genomes for both genera were determined recently, and they confirmed the lack of affinity to 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heteropterinae">Heteropterinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-34107-1" author="Han, Y" journalOrPublisher="British Museum (Natural History), London" pageId="11" pageNumber="102" refId="B14" refString="Han, Y, Huang, Z, Tang, J, Chiba, H, Fan, X, 2018. . https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-34107-1" url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-34107-1" year="2018">Han et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). However, in the absence of 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Trapezitinae">Trapezitinae</taxonomicName>
mitogenome, the two genera remained in 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hesperiinae">Hesperiinae</taxonomicName>
. Our phylogenies place the two genera as sister to 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Trapezitinae">Trapezitinae</taxonomicName>
, thus they may not belong to 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hesperiinae">Hesperiinae</taxonomicName>
. This placement is unexpected because there are no obvious morphological features than unify 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Trapezitinae">Trapezitinae</taxonomicName>
and the two genera. Therefore, we decided on the level of a subfamily for these two unusual skippers. They form an ancient phylogenetic group, and placing them within 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="99" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Trapezitinae">Trapezitinae</taxonomicName>
seems unfitting due to the lack of morphological affinities.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
